---
title: "Workspace Evolution 2021-2026"
tags: painting
date: 2026-04-08
layout: post
---

<!-- Image 1 -->
![image-20260408120234673](image-20260408120234673.png)

My workspace evolved quite a bit between 2021 and 2026. These are photos I took without any particular goal, but they show how things changed over the years. It's about to evolve even more because we're doing renovations in the basement to make something really custom. The photo you see above stayed like this the longest. It was more or less the version that worked best for me, and it stayed in that state for quite a while, to the point where I stopped trying to optimize it.

<!-- Image 2 -->
![image-20260408120301382](image-20260408120301382.png)

This is how it was at the start. I stacked IKEA furniture called TROFAST. They're actually furniture meant for kids to store their stuff in bins. I had put a bunch of things randomly in the bins. But in the end, I didn't find it super practical. It takes up a lot of space and I can't see what's in the bins. The bins can be too small to fit things properly. I think I needed a bit more granularity in what I wanted.

<!-- Image 3 -->
![image-20260408120309393](image-20260408120309393.png)

This is a bit of a zoom. I had started to set something up with whatever was lying around. We had just moved into this house. And these were the furniture pieces we had left that we didn't know what to do with. In the end, the dimensions weren't super practical. It took up a lot of space, I didn't like it that much.

<!-- Image 4 -->
![image-20260408120318069](image-20260408120318069.png)

I realize how small my work surface is. And the storage surface is huge but my stock isn't optimized at all.

<!-- Image 5 -->
![image-20260408120327270](image-20260408120327270.png)

This is after I invested in special boxes. I can't remember what they're called, from Eastern Europe. I don't remember exactly where it's located. They're blocks that all have the same dimensions. Either they're just simple shelves, drawers, large drawers, small drawers. They can stack on top of each other. They're made with magnets, so they fit together very well. I had bought quite a few to set something up. And this is what I managed to do with them. It was pretty good, it was starting to be really a good thing. And you can see they served me for a long time.

<!-- Image 6 -->
![image-20260408120336800](image-20260408120336800.png)

This is after using it a bit more. I bought more to make the corner on the side. In the end, what I discovered with this is that the big, long drawers weren't very interesting for me. I prefer to use them as shelves. It's easier for me to see what's there directly, rather than having to open a drawer to get it. So that was a first lesson. And the more shelves I have, the more pleasant it is for me.

<!-- Image 7 -->
![image-20260408120345577](image-20260408120345577.png)

This is another shelf I had on the side, where I stored all the terrain pieces I had made. Because I didn't really know where to put them. This kind of stuff takes up a lot of space. Today, I think I've given away or thrown out half of them. It was fun to make at the time but I never used them. I realize they served to learn techniques, but they never really served in an actual game or anything. So I ended up throwing most of them away.

<!-- Image 8 -->
![image-20260408120352796](image-20260408120352796.png)

I had made the top of a shelf with some other elements to make a kind of diorama where I could put some of my miniatures. 

<!-- Image 9 -->
![image-20260408120400914](image-20260408120400914.png)

This is starting to be how my workspace functioned. I was painting a lot of terrain at the time, so I needed lots of acrylic paints, that's what you see on the side, and putting them horizontally like this allowed me to find colors directly. Over the years, I reduced the mass because in the end, I was always using the same greys, the same browns, the same greens, and so all the more special colors, I ended up removing them and putting them in another box elsewhere. I had heaps and heaps of brushes, but similarly, I don't need hundreds of brushes as I often use the same ones.

<!-- Image 10 -->
![image-20260408120409020](image-20260408120409020.png)

These are other IKEA furniture that are normally made to store sheets of paper, but which I used to store my miniatures. I had miniatures that were in closed drawers where I couldn't see them, and this was my solution to be able to see them, because I'm happy to see the miniatures I have once I've finished painting them.

The problem is that I only see the miniatures at the front, and even then, I only see half because there's a big bar that blocks them, so I don't really see what's behind. If I need them for a game, it's easy to go get them, it's a bit complicated to put them back, because you have to make sure they stand upright, etc. So it was okay, but it wasn't great yet.

<!-- Image 11 -->
![image-20260408120416317](image-20260408120416317.png)

I had furniture with lots of plastic drawers normally for storing screws, nails, DIY materials, and I used them to store my small terrain elements. It was a false good idea because it really constrained me to store the same similar things in the same drawer, and so when you're in the middle of a game and you need something, it's hard to find exactly what you want.

<!-- Image 12 -->
![image-20260408120425056](image-20260408120425056.png)

The large drawers that are the most practical. That's what I ended up using later, storing miniatures by type. I have a drawer for everything that's bandits, a drawer for everything that's guards, a drawer for everything that's kobolds, another for everything that's goblins. And in fact, it's enough for my RPG sessions, because it allows me to store about twenty at a time inside, and my players will never fight more than 20 guards at once, or 20 kobolds at once. So that's a very good format for me. 

The smaller drawers are way too small for me and forces me to be way too specific into what goes where. Today I have larger ones where I put, for example, all the scatter terrain you can find in a cave, scatter terrain you can find in a manor, or everything you can find in a house, etc. I'll post photos of that later.

<!-- Image 13 -->
![image-20260408120435024](image-20260408120435024.png)

This is another corner of my room in the basement. You can see how it's organized. You see the white furniture with my miniatures. Below, there are lots of drawers with terrain elements. And below, the IKEA furniture with the bins is a bit of the materials for crafting in bulk. Inside, I have lots of foam scraps, or I have lots of plastic toys.

And in the corner, in the boxes, were the terrain pieces I had already made, and which I stored in boxes like that, where the big box at the very top, you can vaguely see a Playmobil boat inside and other Playmobil elements, where I told myself that one day, I would do something with it. All of that, I bought it for cheap when I was just beginning to learn how to craft, telling myself it would be easy to make terrain with. Yes, it's easy, but it's not very useful, so I ended up giving them to kids.

<!-- Image 14 -->
![image-20260408120443381](image-20260408120443381.png)

This is a very good representation of how it generally looks on my workspace. I do several things at the same time. There, you can see I'm making tiles on one side, but I'm also assembling miniatures, I'm also putting other things away.

<!-- Image 15 -->
![image-20260408120450941](image-20260408120450941.png)

This is the contents of one of my drawers. I had put different boxes that were the right height to be placed flat in the drawer, and in each one, I put scatter terrain based on their size and based on their quality. 

Some boxes have "real" scatter, coming from "real" miniature companies like Reaper or Mantic. Other boxes contains stuff that has nice textures, that has interesting things that I recovered from toys and that I kept telling myself it could be useful for something. It was a good way to rummage around to get ideas.

<!-- Image 16 -->
![image-20260408120457402](image-20260408120457402.png)

Finally, I made myself a drawer with all my paints. I glued strips of cardboard at the bottom to separate it in lines. In it are the paints I really use. 

At the bottom left, we have everything for skin, then it's for everything that's cadaveric skin or bones, and then it's everything I use for leather, fur, wood, all the little details on lots of miniatures. These somewhat neutral but fitting colors I put at the bottom right. 

The line above is a kind of rainbow of different colors I use regularly. And the line above, we have at the start everything that's black and grey, then it's rather dark colors but that are a bit tinted, and then it's lots of different greens for when I want to make a kind of camouflage. 

Above I have the Fanatic War Paints because they're extremely well pigmented, and these I often use for drybrushing. Above we have metallic paints and some other things, and at the very top we have washes and I also have some Games Workshop effect paints.

And this system of being able to open my drawer on my left and see all the paints directly with their colors easily and it's well organized, it's perfect for me because it allows me to see exactly what I want, to take exactly what I want, and to make a little list of the colors I like and I remove those I don't like. I have a big box next to it of colors I bought and that I end up never using.

